  1. Which genre has the highest critic rating? Viewer rating?
#subset to only critic rating, aggregate by genre and viewer type 
question_1 <- aggregate(x = cbind(average_rating) ~ reviewer_type +  genre, 
                data = entire_reviews, 
                FUN = mean,
                na.action = na.pass)

#separating data based on reviewer type to find the average for each  
question_1c <- question_1[ question_1$reviewer_type == "Critic", ]

question_1v <- question_1[ question_1$reviewer_type == "Viewer", ]


 
question_1c$genre[which.max( question_1c$average_rating)]
[1] "Comedy"
question_1v$genre[which.max( question_1v$average_rating)]
[1] "Drama"
#finding position of genre with max avg rating and telling r to return the name of the genre in that position
  1. What is the relationship between movie length and average rating?
#for the following questions 2-5, using correlation to measure the strength and direction of the linear relationship between these two variables 
#If the result is close to 1, it indicates that longer movies tend to have higher average ratings.
#If the result is close to -1, it indicates that longer movies tend to have lower average ratings.
#If the result is close to 0, it indicates no significant relationship between movie length and average rating.
#Using ggplot to express the relationship visually 

 relationship_2 <- aggregate(x = cbind(average_rating, total_movie_mins) ~ title + genre, 
                data = entire_reviews, 
                FUN = mean,
                na.action = na.pass)
 
 cor(relationship_2$total_movie_mins, relationship_2$average_rating)
[1] -0.04987857
 library(ggplot2)

ggplot(data = relationship_2, mapping = aes(x = total_movie_mins, y = average_rating)) + geom_point() + 
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE) +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(x = "Movie Length", y = "Average Rating", 
       title = "Relationship Between Movie Length and Average Rating")
`geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'
#decided to include proper labeling of axis and a title 
#the correlation shows that there is an extremely extremely weak relationship (-0.04987857) to the average rating in regards to the movie length. Almost no correlation.
  1. What is the relationship between the date delta and average rating?
#assigned each aggregation in regards to the question I am answering 

 relationship_3 <- aggregate(x = cbind(date_delta_date, average_rating) ~ title + genre, 
                data = entire_reviews, 
                FUN = mean,
                na.action = na.pass)

cor(relationship_3$date_delta_date, relationship_3$average_rating)
[1] -0.2430595
library(ggplot2)
ggplot(data = relationship_3, mapping = aes(x = date_delta_date, y = average_rating)) + geom_point() + 
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE) +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(x = "Date Delta", y = "Average Rating", 
       title = "Relationship Between Date Delta and Average Rating")
`geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'
#the correlation is -0.2430595, which suggests a weak negative relationship, but there is still a correlation showing that when the time between the movie being released and rated is longer the average rating is worse.
  1. What is the relationship between total number of reviews and average?
relationship_4 <- aggregate(x = cbind(total_reviews, average_rating) ~ title + genre, 
                data = entire_reviews, 
                FUN = mean,
                na.action = na.pass)

cor(relationship_4$average_rating, relationship_4$total_reviews)
[1] 0.4737859
library(ggplot2)
ggplot(data = relationship_4, mapping = aes(x = average_rating, y = total_reviews)) + geom_point() + 
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE) +
  theme_minimal() +
    labs(x = "Average Rating", y = "Total Reviews", 
       title = "Relationship Between Total Number of Reviews and Average")
`geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'
#Between total number of reviews and average there is a moderate positive degree of correlation (0.4). This suggests that movies with more reviews tend to have higher average ratings.

relationship_5 <- aggregate(x = disaster_count ~ title,  
                data = entire_reviews, 
                FUN = sum,
                na.action = na.pass)

relationship_5 <- merge(relationship_5, unique_movie, by = 'title')


cor(relationship_5$disaster_count,relationship_5$average_rating)
[1] -0.4001778
library(ggplot2)

#included color 

ggplot(data = relationship_5, mapping = aes(x = disaster_count, y = average_rating, group = disaster_count)) +
    geom_boxplot(color = "blue") + 
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(x = "Disaster Count", y = "Average Rating", 
       title = "Relationship Between 'Disaster' Count and Average Rating")
#The box plot is a great way of expressing the correlation. When the movie rating increases, the use of the word disaster decreases. The correlation is moderate negative -0.4
